title --harden-home built: deny real credential-store reads, honest test limit named
prompt Keaton said yes to the recommended path from the security question and asked for a Rish script he could run in an outside terminal to do the key copying.
think chose a deny-only, named-credential-store-paths design over a blanket-deny-dotfiles-then-allow-back design after discovering empirically (precedence_probe.rish, deleted after use) that Apple's Seatbelt on this host resolves an overlapping allow/deny pair to deny, regardless of rule order or specificity -- a literal (allow file-read* (literal .../.gitconfig)) placed even *before* an overlapping (deny file-read* (regex ...)) still denied. A blanket approach would have silently broken git identity and shell rc reads; naming only the actual credential stores (~/.ssh, ~/.gnupg, ~/.aws, ~/.config/gh, ~/.terraform.d, ~/.docker, ~/.kube, ~/.azure, ~/.gcloud, ~/.codeberg-token, ~/.netrc, ~/.git-credentials, ~/.npmrc) sidesteps the trap entirely since there is no overlap to resolve.
think built --harden-home into both the Rish-native launcher (tools/cursor_jail_macos.rish) and its bash elder (tools/cursor-jail-macos.sh), keeping the two in lockstep as the file's own convention already establishes. Hit a real Rish ordering bug along the way: the dq/nl double-quote fixtures were defined *after* the new harden_* lines that referenced them, producing UndefinedName -- moved the fixture reads earlier, fixed on the first real syntax pass.
think discovered a second real environmental fact while trying to self-test: an `exec sandbox-exec ...` command replaced this persistent shell's own process image mid-session, killing the terminal Cursor was tracking (visible as repeated "shell command returned no exit status" on every subsequent command) -- recovered by passing a working_directory override on the next Shell call, which spun up a fresh terminal. Named this as a real hazard: never `exec` a foreign binary directly in a persistent tool-managed shell.
think built tools/cursor_jail_macos_harden_witness.rish to prove the read-deny semantics, and hit a subtler trap: the witness's early PASS results for ~/.ssh and ~/.gnupg denial were false positives -- sandbox_apply itself was failing outright for the *whole* hardened profile (not denying the specific file), because a *nested* sandbox_apply carrying an explicit (deny ...) rule fails on this host even though the identical profile applies cleanly as a first, non-nested call, and even though an allow-only nested profile (the existing plain write-fence witness) nests without issue. Proved this by testing a hand-written minimal profile (baseline-that-demonstrably-works plus exactly one appended deny line) and watching it fail identically and deterministically, every time, ruling out a session-level flake or profile-content bug.
think fixed the witness's own honesty rather than papering over the finding: added an up-front apply_probe (a trivial `true` command through the same profile) whose failure now reports plainly "run this witness from an unsandboxed terminal" instead of letting a coincidental exit-code match masquerade as a real deny-proof. Documented the same limit in the witness's own header, in SOURCE.md, and in the macOS guide -- an agent already working inside a jailed window genuinely cannot self-certify --harden-home from inside that same window; this needed naming, not hiding.
think built tools/generate_jail_local_keys_macos.rish for Keaton to run outside any jail, deliberately keeping key *creation* off any agent-controlled process -- generates a passphrase-free SSH deploy key per forge and a passphrase-free signing-only GPG key, all under this project's own gitignored .ssh/ and .gnupg-rye/, printing exactly what to paste into GitHub's and Codeberg's key settings without attempting the registration itself (a human act, on purpose).
think syntax-tested the key generator end to end in an isolated /tmp scratch directory (copying only the script and the rishi binary, never touching the real .ssh/.gnupg-rye) rather than running it for real inside this jail -- confirmed it produces valid-looking SSH and GPG public keys and prints the expected paste instructions, then deleted every scratch artifact immediately, honoring the same "the agent should not be the one minting the dedicated keys" principle the script itself states in its own header.
obs this closes the real exploit chain named in the prior turn's security-question log (open reads plus open network needs no write to exfiltrate a real identity) for the specific credential stores that matter, while being honest that it is not the full private-$HOME upstream ai-jail gives CLI agents -- named plainly as the remaining gap in both SOURCE.md and the guide's own "What Is Still Open" section.
obs the "deny always wins an overlap" finding and the "nested sandbox_apply with a deny rule fails" finding are both new, previously-undocumented facts about Seatbelt on this specific host, discovered only through direct, repeated, falsifiable testing rather than assumed from general sandbox theory -- both are now written down so no future session has to rediscover them the hard way.
file tools/cursor_jail_macos.rish -- --harden-home flag; deny-only named credential-store list; header comments corrected to match the final deny-only design (not the earlier, abandoned blanket-deny-then-allow-back draft)
file tools/cursor-jail-macos.sh -- --harden-home mirrored in the bash elder, same deny list, same comments
file tools/cursor_jail_macos_harden_witness.rish -- new; proves the deny list, with an up-front apply-probe that turns a possible false-positive into an honest, correctly-labeled failure
file tools/generate_jail_local_keys_macos.rish -- new; generates dedicated jail-local SSH + GPG materials, meant to run outside any jail, prints paste-ready public keys
file .gitignore -- explicit /.ssh/ entry added beside the existing /.gnupg-rye/ and /.gnupg/ local-key-material lines
file SOURCE.md -- Step 8's macOS section rewritten from "not required yet" to the built --harden-home flow, plus the honest self-testing limit; version bumped 20260714.081500
file manual/guides/macos-ai-jail-setup.md -- new "Denying the Real Credential Stores (--harden-home)" section; "What You Get" and "What Is Still Open" updated to match; version bumped 20260714.081500
file session-logs/20260714-081500_harden_home_built_and_named_test_limit.bron -- this log
recommend check-in -- before Keaton actually runs tools/generate_jail_local_keys_macos.rish for real and relaunches with --harden-home, this is worth his own read-through first: it changes what this jail can and cannot see, and the honest self-testing limit means the final proof that --harden-home behaves as intended has to come from his own outside-terminal run of the witness, not from this session's own (partially blocked) attempts. Once he confirms the witness is green from outside, the next mechanical step returns to the Neth ladder's two-posture root install.
